<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Irish Ruling Group Lags Behind in Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Irish Prime Minister John Bruton's
ruling coalition lags 10 points behind its chief opponents in the
run-up to national elections next Friday, according to a poll
published by The Irish Times newspaper today.
</P>
<P>
The survey put support for the main opposition Fianna Fail and
smaller Progressive Democratic party at a combined 49 percent,
bringing them close to securing a majority in the Dail, the Irish
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The total support for Fine Gael, led by Bruton and his partner
Labor and Democratic Left parties, was 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
The poll was conducted among 1,000 electors at 100 sampling
points in all constituencies last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish Republican Army
fighting against British rule in neighboring Northern Ireland,
says it can win a seat. It gained two British parliamentary seats
in Britain's May 1 general election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
