<HEADLINE> Counties to be China's Huge Potential Market, Says Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, May 31 (Xinhua) -- County-level administrative areas,
which hold 80 percent of China's population, are a huge potential
market, one economic reform expert says.
</P>
<P>
An Zhiwen, the director of the Research Office of China's
Restructuring, said here today research on developing the
county economy in central and western parts of China, an
economically disadvantaged region, has been a priority.
</P>
<P>
Counties contributed 60 percent of the country's GDP in 1996,
and more than 40 percent of its revenue and these figures are
increasing. Links should be made between coastal and inland
enterprises, An said.
</P>
<P>
This would benefit industrial improvement in coastal areas and
large and medium-sized cities to develop potential markets in
counties nearby, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Reforms and the growth in township businesses have brought
fundmental changes in the economic structure of China's rural
areas in the past 18 years. During that time, 130 million Chinese
farmers changed to secondary and service industries, while grain
output increased from 200 billion kg to 500 billion.
</P>
<P>
An said that increases in farmers' incomes and purchasing power
have played an important role in making rural areas a buyer's
market. Retail sales at or below the county level now account for
half the country's retail sales, and that could be nearly 70
percent when farmers' expenditures in cities are added in.
</P>
</TEXT>
