<HEADLINE> Children across China Celebrate Holiday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- From Tian'anmen Square in the
capital of Beijing to Lhasa on the "roof of the world," Chinese
children today held an array of colorful activities to mark their
own holiday, International Children's Day, which falls on June 1.
</P>
<P>
China is home to three million children, the majority of whom
live in its vast rural areas. Youngsters in the relatively poor
regions realized today they have not been forgotten by adults and
other kids in the country.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Li Lanqing and his wife, and Minister of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation Wu Yi, together with children from
Beijing watched this evening's annual charity concert to raise
funds for school dropouts in the rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The concert series, which started back in 1994, has
successfully raised funds to set up three primary schools.
</P>
<P>
Entrepreneurs in Xi'an, home of the world-renowned terra-cotta
warriors, held an event to donate books and school materials for
kids in the province's poor regions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in Shanghai, the country's economic powerhouse,
children visited a special show of toys and children's books. The
exhibit hall, complete with multimedia computers, was the hottest
venue for incoming little visitors, who enjoyed electronic games
and calling their new-found friends in Beijing with the aid of a
video-conferencing system.
</P>
<P>
The return of Hong Kong to the embrace of the motherland has
become another popular theme for the children's celebrations.
</P>
<P>
A group of Tibetan children in Lhasa, capital of the Tibet
Autonomous Region, sang and danced at the foot of the Potala
Palace. "I'm a little Tibetan child, living under the feet of the
snow mountain... I'm a child from beautiful Hong Kong," the chorus
rang out.
</P>
<P>
Children performing in Beijing set up a countdown clock on
stage to express their eagerness for the rejoining of the "Pearl
of the Orient" to its ancestral land.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the show, a group of children from both Beijing
and Hong Kong, hand in hand, danced to the accompaniment of a song
titled "Seeking Friends." And a slogan written on the backdrop of
the stage read "We love the motherland, and we love Hong Kong."
</P>
</TEXT>
