<HEADLINE> Tudjman Denies Charges of Ethnic Purity Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Croatian President Franjo Tudjman on
Saturday denied that the policy of his government is aimed at
making Croatia a pure nation country.
</P>
<P>
"Croatia is not embarking on any policy of ethnic purity but
rather recognizes fully all human and ethnic rights of all
communities in this country, including Serbs," Tudjman said after
his meeting with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
"It is our challenge to create as soon as possible the
conditions for co-existene" of different nations in Croatia,
Tudjman added.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Croatian government respected the right of
Serbs who had fled Croatia during the 1991-95 war to return and
that it would continue to comply with the other aspects of the
Dayton peace accords.
</P>
<P>
Albright hinted that if Croatia prevented the return of Serb
refugees, Washington would block Croatia's desired integration
with wealthy European countries.
</P>
<P>
"Croatia will not travel the road to Europe unless all its
peoples, Croats and Serbs, make the journey," she said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that during the meeting with Croatian leaders,
Albright also threatened to veto the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) Loans to Croatia, if it failed to take required measures on
the issues of refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
