<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel: Stolen Car Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Despite the prevalence of
various modern alarm systems, Israel is still the stolen car
capital of the world, with five car-thefts occurring every hour.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest Israeli Police statistics, every 12
minutes a car is reported missing, and insurance companies paid
off over 1 billion shekels (some 300 million U.S. dollars)
against car thieves last year.
</P>
<P>
Several bigger Israeli insurance companies are now sponsoring
a special police unit, using helicopters, to fight the car-theft
plague.
</P>
<P>
Israeli police said that some 80 percent of the stolen cars end
up in the Palestinian autonomous areas, as the motor repairing
industry is flourishing in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
"As long as we have poor people live next to rich people,
there will always be a flow of properties from the richer side to
the poorer side," officials from insurance companies said.
</P>
<P>
Many Palestinians, prevented from working inside Israel because
of the closure imposed by Israel on Palestinian autonomous
areas, are making easy money by bringing the stolen cars to one
of the West Bank repairing yards, according to the police.
</P>
<P>
Israeli soldiers at various check points look up suspicious
vehicles, but local Palestinians can always find their way by
using many unpoliced back roads, they said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli police want cooperation from the Palestinian
police in fighting against the car crime, and in fact, the
Palestinian Authority did return hundreds of cars to Israel.
</P>
<P>
"In an atmosphere of real peace, this kind of cooperation
is demanded every day, every hour," said Jerusalem city
council member, Ornan Yekutieli, whose stolen car was found
and returned by Palestinian Police last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
