<HEADLINE> Ukraine, Russia Sign Friendship Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma and
his Russian counterpart, Boris Yeltsin, today signed a Treaty of
Friendship, Cooperation and Partnership, straightening twisted
relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Under the treaty, the two countries should respect each other's
sovereignty and territorial integrity, not violate the present
borders, nor interfere in each other's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the treaty requires the two parties not to pressure on
each other by military or economic means and not to form alliance
with a third country to oppose the other.
</P>
<P>
The treaty is a historic event in bilateral relations, Yeltsin
and Kuchma claimed.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference after the signing ceremony, Kuchma
stressed that disputes over the port city of Sevastopol have now
ended.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said the treaty is adopted in accordance with the
wishes of the peoples of the two countries, adding that Ukraine
and Russia are two equal democratic nations.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma said that neither Russia nor Ukraine make any
concessions in dividing the Black Sea Fleet and interests of both
have been safeguarded.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin expressed his satisfaction with the treaty, saying that
the treaty has given no problems to the future relations of the
two nations, and vowed that Russia and Ukraine would work
together to build Sevastopol.
</P>
<P>
Russia and Ukraine, the two biggest former Soviet republics,
have been at odds since the former Soviet Union disintegrated in
1991, and their relations hurt because of conflicting claims to
the Black Sea Fleet and its main base Sevastopol.
</P>
<P>
The two countries reached three agreements on dividing the
fleet on May 28 when Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin
visited Ukraine, ending two years of quarrels and making Yeltsin's
visit a reality. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
