<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-31 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Appeals to Europe to Help Lift Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi National Assembly
(parliament) Speaker Saadoun Hammadi has appealed to European
parliaments to help lift without delay the sanctions imposed on
Iraq, the official Iraqi news agency (INA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to participants in the ongoing meeting of the
European Parliament held in Helsinki, Finland, Hammadi said Iraq
has met its obligations under the U.N. Security Council's
resolution 687 and that it has positively cooperated with the
U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of disarming weapons of
mass destruction in the country.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Security Council has to reciprocate by
putting into effect paragraph 22 of resolution 687 which provides
for the lifting of the almost seven-year sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Stringent sanctions were imposed on Iraq by the Security
Council immediately after Iraqi troops invaded Kuwait in August,
1990.
</P>
<P>
The most important prerequisite to lifting the sanctions is the
UNSCOM's confirmation that Iraq has fulfilled all its obligations
of its disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Hammadi stated that the sanctions have caused the deaths of
about 830,000 Iraqis up to April this year because of the lack of
food, medicine, baby milk and other basic necessities.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the need for the European Parliament to make
known the facts about the sanctions to the public in their
relative countries, but he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, the speaker also blamed "an influential power
in the Security Council" for the continuation of the
sanctions, a reference to the United States.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has submitted to the U.N. sanction committee hundreds of
contracts with foregin countries for its purchase of food and
medicine and other daily necessities, but only a small part of
them have been approved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
