<HEADLINE> Instant Success for Liu Yong and Ge Fei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GLASGOW, Scotland, May 31 (Xinhua) -- When Chinese head coach
Li Yongbo decided in November to let Liu Yong and Ge Fei team up
to train for mixed doubles, he never dreamed of their chance at
the world title.
</P>
<P>
"I thought they are still young and they could train then for a
medal at the Sydney Olympic Games in 2000," he said after Liu and
Ge beat Denmark's Jens Eriksen and Marlene Thomsen to win the
world championships here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Since their international outing early this year, the
invincible pair won Japan Open, South Korea Open, Swiss Open
before romping to victory at All England title in March.
</P>
<P>
They share many characteristics in personality. Unlike many
good introvert-extrovert combination for doubles event, both are
quiet but happy people who seem to smile always.
</P>
<P>
Both were born in Jiangsu Province in 1975, the Chinese year of
Rabbit. But on the court, the two "rabbits" transform into an
aggressive pair that fights in concord and precision.
</P>
<P>
Ge Fei is the creative one with excellent control and touch at
the net while Liu Yong holds the key of mixed doubles success with
good serving skills and backcourt ability.
</P>
<P>
Ge also played in the women's doubles while Liu competed in
men's doubles, but both appeared to have little problem physically.
</P>
<P>
"We are young at 21 years. And the rigorous systematic training
ensures us good physical abilities," said Liu.
</P>
<P>
And the pair is aiming high, despite their immediate goal is to
win the October's National Games for home Jiangsu province.
</P>
<P>
"Of course we want to win more international events," Liu said,
when a smiling Ge looked on. 
</P>
</TEXT>
