<HEADLINE> IAAF Bans Slaney for Positive Dope Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, May 31 (Xinhua) -- American runner Mary Slaney has been
banned from competition after a positive dope test, according to a
Saturday decision by the International Amateur Athletic Federation
(IAAF).
</P>
<P>
Sandra Farmer-Patrick, another American runner, was banned by
the U.S. Track and Field Association for four years earlier this
month for testing positive for the steroid testosterone, but
Reineri said the IAAF had yet to be informed of the ban.
</P>
<P>
IAAF president Primo Nebiolo said all athletes testing positive
would from now on be suspended immediately.
</P>
<P>
"If a federation is reluctant to act immediately in accordance
with IAAF rules, then the IAAF Council will from now on suspend
the athlete until the national federation decides (a ban or not),"
he told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
The IAAF decision was prompted by what it considered to be the
sluggish handling of the doping cases involving Farmer-Patrick and
Slaney by the U.S. Track and Field Association.
</P>
<P>
Farmer-Patrick ran in the Atlanta Olympics last August despite
the positive test because the case had not been concluded.
</P>
<P>
Slaney's case is not yet over. She was found to have high
levels of testosterone in her body at the U.S. trials last June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970601.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-31 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt's Mediation Does Not Bow to Outside Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak said
today Egypt's mediating efforts to restore the Mideast peace
process are based on its own interests, without bowing to any
pressure.
</P>
<P>
The president said during discussions with Egypt's leading
media staff on the occasion of the 14th Media Day that Egypt
cooperates with the United States and all other concerned parties
to achieve peace in the Middle East but "it does not accept
pressure from any quarter or any country."
</P>
<P>
Speculations have it that the U.S. pressure is behind
stepped-up Egyptian role in the Mideast mediation since the
shuttlings by U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross failed to bring the two
sides back to the negotiating table. Egypt is believed to be
siding with the Palestinians in mediating an end to the peace
crisis with Israel.
</P>
<P>
"Our decision is an Egyptian decision dictated by
national considerations and Egypt's interests," Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
Information Minister Safwat al-Sherif said after the meeting
that Mubarak has stressed that Egypt does not negotiate on behalf
of the Palestinians or others.
</P>
<P>
"They are the people concerned," he quoted the president as
saying, "Egypt's role is to bring Palestinian and Israeli views
closer."
</P>
<P>
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks broke down in March when Israel
began building expansion of Jewish settlement in Har Homa in Arab
East Jerusalem. The Palestinians have made their return to the
negotiating table conditional on a halt of Israel's expansionary
policy.
</P>
<P>
The president described the Har Homa settlement, a contentious
issue taking central stage in the two-month-old peace crisis, "a
small problem compared to other problems which are more serious."
He stressed that the Jerusalem issue should be settled within the
framework of final status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak was reportedly floating a five-point plan to persuade
the two sides back to the table, which includes a temporary halt of
settlement activities in Jerusalem and the West Bank and the
immediate resumption of the final talks.
</P>
<P>
He also underlined the importance of breaking the deadlock
in the peace process, referring to his meeting with Israeli Prime
Minister Binjamin Netanyahu in the Red Sea resort of Sharm
el-Sheikh last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The Mideast cause is complicated and problems cannot be solved
overnight," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
