<HEADLINE> World Labor Body to Launch Child Labor Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The International Labor
Organization (ILO) will carry out major surveys in southern
Africa on child labor to make clear how serious the situation is.
</P>
<P>
ILO Director for southern Africa Peter Peek said here today
the governments in the region were willing to fight child labor
but constrained by lack of accurate information on the extent of
the problem in their own countries.
</P>
<P>
He said when the surveys are completed, the ILO would start
action programs aimed at solving the problems in identified
areas.
</P>
<P>
The first survey would start in South Africa in October this
year while discussions with the Zimbabwean government on the
survey has reached advanced stages so far, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he urged African governments to continue
strengthening their labor laws in order to ensure the protection
of their citizens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
