<HEADLINE> East Africa to Share Tax Information </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania, Kenya and Uganda,
all the three member states of the East African Cooperation
(EAC), decided today to share information about taxpayers and tax
administration in general.
</P>
<P>
The resolution was approved today during a one-day
consultative meeting of the EAC commissioners general held here
today.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by Commissioner General of Tanzania Revenue
Authority M. E. Sanare said the information the region agreed to
share include reforms to the tax structures, revenue collection,
investment incentives, and documentation systems and procedures.
</P>
<P>
On harmonization of customs documents in the three countries,
Sanare, who was the chairman of the meeting, said the meeting
reviewed the progress made in the standardization of customs
documents used in the three countries.
</P>
<P>
He said the decision aims to facilitate business across the
common borders and to promote the inner-EAC investment.
</P>
<P>
The three states also agreed to boost the effectiveness of
pre-shipment inspection services and to strengthen the
coordination and reinforcement of patrols and escort of transit
goods so as to curb border smuggling, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
