<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Urges Completion of Somali Reconciliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) today stressed
the necessity of accomplishing national reconciliation among
various Somali factions and offered support and assistance to the
process.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement today, AL Assistant Secretary General
Ahmed Bin Hali, who is in charge of the Somalia file, said that a
recent Agreement increased success opportunities of national
reconciliation in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Somali faction leaders reached the agreement here Thursday on
holding peaceful talks to end the civil war that has ravaged the
country since 1991.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's reconciliation agreement was signed by Ali Mahdi
Mohammed, chief of the Somali Salvation Alliance and Hussein
Farah Aideed, head of the United Somali Congress.
</P>
<P>
"It provides for ceasing hostilities and solving problems
between the Somalis through peaceful means," said Hali, who called
for an early definition of the venue and date of the projected
conference on national reconciliation in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
He also pledged full support and "various kinds of aid" for
making any such conference a success.
</P>
<P>
"The Arab League will pursue its endeavors that are aimed at
bringing Somalia back to normal in order to play its role at
Arab, African and world arenas," he added.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, a conference of national reconciliation
will be held inside the country in the coming months to remove
the remaining differences among the Somali people.
</P>
<P>
AL Secretary General Esmat Abdul-Meguid held intensive talks
over the past few months with the Somali faction leaders with the
aim of bringing closer viewpoints and removing differences
between the parties.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, together with other African countries, has also been
involved in mediating an end to the six-year-old Somali crisis in
the previous few months.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1991 ouster of the late President Mohammed Siad
Barre, Somalia has been fragmented into fiefdoms protected by
faction leaders, who continued to fight to expand their turfs
despite several unsuccessful peace conferences.
</P>
<P>
The factional fightings combined with a 1992 famine have
claimed about 350,000 lives in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
