<HEADLINE> GCC Calls for Turkish Pullout from Northern Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministers of the six
Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states today called on Turkey to
withdraw from northern Iraq, reports reaching here from Saudi
capital Riyadh said.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwait News Agency (KUNA) said the call was made by Qatari
Foreign Minister Sheikh Hamad Ben Jassem Bin Jaber al Thani, also
chairman of the current GCC ministerial council, at the
inaugural session of a two-day meeting in the Saudi capital of
Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
He said the council expressed their regret over the Turkish
military incursion into northern Iraq and the Turkish violation
of Iraqi territorial sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
He said, "the Turkish military operation is a serious threat
to the security and stability of the region and international
peace as well."
</P>
<P>
For two weeks the Turkish troops have been operating in
northern Iraq to against Turkish rebels of the Kurdish Workers'
Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting is the 63rd of its kind by foreign
ministers of the GCC, namely Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United
Arab Emirates (UAE), Bahrain, Qatar and Oman, since the founding
of the regional political and economic block in 1981.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Sheikh Hamad also congratulated newly-elected
Iranian President Mohammad Khatami on his victory in the recent
Iranian election.
</P>
<P>
Hamad also expressed hope that the GCC-Iranian relations
would develop further during his term of office, especially with
regard to the territorial dispute between the UAE and Iran over
the islands of Abu Moussa and Greater and Lesser Tunbs.
</P>
<P>
Khatami reaffirmed the Iranian sovereignty over the three islands
at his first press conference after election, but expressed
willingness to start talks on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the GCC members sent greetings to congratulate
Khatami on his landslide victory in the elections.
</P>
<P>
The Qatari foreign minister also voiced regret on behalf of
the GCC states at the deterioration of the Middle East peace
process due to Israel's anti-Arab policies.
</P>
<P>
He called on Israel to remain committed to complying with
agreements with the Palestinians, halt the construction of the
new Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem and adhere to
Madrid's conference and the U.N. Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the Jewish state to resume peace negotiations
with Syria from where they stopped and complete withdrawal from
the Golan Heights, south Lebanon and Western Beqaa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
