<HEADLINE> S. Leone's Coupists Seek Peace with Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Coup leaders that toppled the
elected government in Sierra Leone a week ago said today they are
in negotiations with sub-regional leaders to resolve political
crisis and restore peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
However, the situation in Sierra Leone remains tense, the
Nigeria Television Authority reported tonight.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the military regime led by Major
Johnny Paul Koroma has set up checkpoints around the capital
Freetown as west African countries may intervene militarily to
reverse last Sunday's coup.
</P>
<P>
Ghanian troops are reportedly marching towards the border of
Sierra Leone while other west African countries may try to
re-install ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, it said.
</P>
<P>
The report said the Revolutionary United Front rebels who have
been fighting a civil war in the country for the past five years
have come to Freetown following the call of the new military
leaders for the return of their former leader Foday Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh was reportedly detained in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
A Nigerian delegation led by chief of defence staff
Major-General A. Abubakar has been in Freetown since Wednesday to
discuss with the coup leaders for a solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The development of the negotiations has not yet been
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Western countries have evacuated their nationals in Freetown
and the military authorities have ordered a closure of borders
for security reason.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. States Department Spokesman, John Dinger, said on
Friday the U.S. opposes to use foreign forces to intervene in
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
But the U.S. would continue to pursue all diplomatic efforts,
including all international pressure possbile, to restore the
democratically elected government in the west African country,
he said. 
</P>
