<HEADLINE> U.S. Refits Nuclear Bomb Against Enemy Bunkers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. has for the first time
since the end of the Cold War put a nuclear weapon with new
capabilities into the field, a "bunker buster" designed to destroy
underground factories or laboratories, a news report said today.
</P>
<P>
"The weapon, called the B-61, is a repackaging of a hydrogen
bomb that has been deployed in the nation's arsenal for 30 years,"
reported the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
The bomb was originally designed to be dropped from an airplane
by parachute and exploded while still aloft.
</P>
<P>
The warhead of the bomb has been fitted into a new,
needle-shaped heavy case. Dropped without a parachute, it can
burrow as deep as 50 feet into the soil before exploding, but
cause relatively little surface damage, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted critics as saying that the re-designed
B-61 is a new weapon intended to be used against small countries
like Iran, Libya, which Washington suspects may be developing
chemical weapons underground.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon officials, however, said the bomb was developed to
address a potential threat from traditional nuclear adversaries
like Russia, stressing it is not a new weapon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
