<HEADLINE> First Private Radio to Start Operation in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's first private radio
station will start its trial operation Monday after getting a
broadcasting license from the government.
</P>
<P>
Radio Sagarmatha, named after what the world's highest Mount
Qomolangma is called in Nepal, is broadcasting educational,
informative and entertainment services for two hours every morning
on a trial basis within the Kathmandu area, sponsors said.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Information and Communications Jhalanath Khanal
today handed over the radio's broadcasting license to the Nepal
Forum of Environmental Journalists (NFEJ), the major sponsor of
Radio Sagarmatha.
</P>
<P>
Khanal said the license was issued as the first step to
liberalize the communications sector under the government's policy
of involving the private sector in the responsibilities so far
being carried out by the state alone.
</P>
<P>
Radio Sagarmatha will become the first non-commercial radio
station operated by the private sector in the South Asian region,
sources from the NFEJ said.
</P>
<P>
They said the radio will extend its daily service time
gradually after a two-month trial period.  
</P>
</TEXT>
