<HEADLINE> N.Irish Policeman Dies After Being Beaten by Mob </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- An off-duty Northern Ireland
policeman died this morning after being beaten by a mob in the
town of Ballymoney in Country Antrim, reports from Belfast said.
</P>
<P>
The reports said at least seven pro-British protestants
assaulted the 45-year-old officer outside a bar. He died from the
injuries several hours later.
</P>
<P>
The protestants targeted the police probably because they were
angered at being barred from holding marches in the past few
months in the County Antrim village of Dunloy after the mainly
anti-British Roman Catholic Irish nationalist residents protested
strongly to the local government.
</P>
<P>
This was the first serious incident after Labor Party won a
landslide victory in the May 1 general election.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, security forces found a bomb detonation wire in west
Belfast as they investigated an IRA claim that it had abandoned a
defused landmine, police said.
</P>
<P>
An IRA statement said one of its units had aborted a planned
attack on security forces on Saturday and left the landmine in a
van in the Poleglass district.
</P>
<P>
It was the IRA's first reported hostile action in the province
for six weeks, during which Britain has resumed contacts broken
off 16 months ago with their political wing.
</P>
<P>
The IRA has been fighting against the British rule of Northern
Ireland over the past 28 years. The new Labor government has
offered to resume official contact with IRA's political wing Sinn
Fein.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of talks were held in the past 10 days, bringing new
hope of a breakthrough in the deadlocked peace process in Northern
Ireland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
