<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rasmussen Beats Sun to Take Men's Singles Crown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GLASGOW, Scotland, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Peter Rasmussen won
Denmark's first world men's singles title in 20 years by battling
two hours to beat China's Sun Jun in a spectacular final at the
World Badminton Championships here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Rasmussen, a 25-year-old student doctor, rallied from one set
down to beat Sun 16-17, 18-13 and 15-10 and won the honor for
Denmark again since Flemming Delfs took the title at the first
World Championships in 1977.
</P>
<P>
Rasmussen, whose deceptive smashes worked well against a
sometimes hesitant Sun, led the first game 14-10 to reach his
first game point, only to see Sun come back to save another game
point on his way to tie the score 14-14.
</P>
<P>
In the three-point setting, Rasmussen got his third game point
at 2-1 but squandered it again to finally concede 16-17.
</P>
<P>
Sun, 22, broke away from a 6-6 tie to lead 13-6 in the second
game. But left-handed Rasmussen then rallied with delicate and
clever net play to tie 13-13 before winning the setting 5-0 with
pinpointed accurate smashes along the lines.
</P>
<P>
In the deciding game, an exhausted Sun managed to lead the game
5-3 when he suffered a cramp but spent several controversial
minutes twice on court to treat his left leg as umpire Chan Chun
Sang of Malaysia watched on.
</P>
<P>
He struggled to win five more points for a 10-3 lead before the
cramp took its toll and a ruthless Rasmussen easily
out-manouveured the staggering Sun to take his very first world
title.
</P>
<P>
Sun won the silver medal. Both Indonesia's Heryanto Arbi and
Denmark's Poul-Erik Hoyer-Larsen were placed third and took the
bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
"It was an incredible experience for me. I was amazed. This is
the hardest match that I have ever played," said Rasmussen at the
post-match press conference.
</P>
<P>
He added, "I opened the court a lot and tried to be patient
before I made the smashes."
</P>
<P>
He said he was not affected by the controversial moment when
Sun disrupted the continuity of match to treat his cramp in the
left leg. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
