<HEADLINE> Italy Revokes Nomination of New Ambassador to Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government revoked the
appointment of Manfredo Incisa di Camerana as new ambassador to
Albania, a statement issued by the foreign ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
"Following the offer by ambassador Manfredo Incisa de Camerana
to renounce the appointment bestowed on him, the government has
decided to revoke the nomination," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The decision came only two days after Incisa was named to take
over the sensitive post from Paolo Foresti.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said the reversal came as the
result of a "rather disconcerting" statement made by the
newly-named ambassador to the press.
</P>
<P>
Incisa, a former ambassador to Mozambique, was quoted in the La
Repubblica newspaper on Saturday as saying that the Italian
Foreign Ministry was going through a period of weakness and
Foresti, his would-be predecessor, had always been
politically-aligned.
</P>
<P>
Today, the newspaper quoted him as saying that his comments had
been off the record and were distorted. At the same time, he had
offered to stand down from the post.
</P>
<P>
Dini added that the decision to revoke the nomination was a
particular event involving an individual who showed he was not up
to the situation, and it would not harm Italy's image.
</P>
<P>
"The situation in Albania is sensitive but there is no
immediate emergency. We have an ambassador with great experience
who has completed his mandate. We should have recalled him some
time ago. So in the next few days, we will manage a new
nomination," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
