<HEADLINE> Tibet Sends Gift To Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The government of the Tibet
Autonomous Region sent a wool tapestry to Shenzhen in southern
China to mark Hong Kong's upcoming return.
</P>
<P>
The tapestry has "Celebrate the Establishment of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region" written on it both in Chinese and
Tibetan and will be presented to Hong Kong on July 1.
</P>
<P>
The tapestry is 240 centimeters long, indicating that the 2.4
million people of various ethnic groups cherish Hong Kong's return
to the embrace of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
In related developments, 1,997 local young people in Tianjin
made some 800 paintings to mark the festive event, and sent them
up into the sky on six huge balloons.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a 48-sq.m. painting was sent to Hong Kong as a gift
from over one million children in Tianjin, with a caption: "Hong
Kong returns Home".
</P>
<P>
The same day, Ke Shouliang, an acrobat and film director from
Hong Kong, jumped the Yellow River in a car at the Hukou Falls
between Shaanxi and Shanxi provinces to mark Hong Kong's upcoming
return.
</P>
<P>
As the date of Hong Kong's return draws near, more festive
activities are expected all over China. 
</P>
