<HEADLINE> Christians Pray For Blessings on Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Christians gathered
here today to pray for blessings upon Hong Kong, which will become
a special administrative region of China on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The grand prayer meeting, held in the open air at the
35,000-seat Hong Kong Stadium, was intended to unite Christians of
different sects to pray for this land before the advent of the
historic moment, said the Reverend Paul C.C. Ng, chairman of the
Executive Committee of the Hong Kong Christians Prayer Convention.
</P>
<P>
Strains of music played by Hong Kong Boys' Brigade Band sounded
at six o'clock in the evening to open the two-hour prayer
convention, which comprises four sessions -- testimony, presence,
commitment and prayer for blessings.
</P>
<P>
In the final prayer, pastors and Christians shared their common
wishes -- pray for a smooth transition in the society of Hong
Kong, and ask for God's grace and glory to be upon this place.
</P>
<P>
The Rev. Mr. Ng said: "The majority of Christians in Hong Kong
are optimistic about the future of Hong Kong, and that's why they
stay here to witness the historic handover."
</P>
<P>
Having served the Hong Kong Council of the Church of Christ In
China for 15 years, the Rev. Mr. Ng was confident that believers
in Hong Kong would continue to enjoy religious freedom after July
1. "The Basic Law ensures that Hong Kong people's life style will
remain unchanged in the next 50 years," he said.
</P>
<P>
The idea of launching a grand Christians prayer meeting first
came to his mind two years ago, and dozens of churches expressed
their support. This year the organizer sent invitations to more
than 1,000 churches and 200 religious organizations across Hong
Kong, asking for their participation.
</P>
<P>
There are about 250,000 to 280,000 Christians in Hong Kong,
including Chinese, Filipinos, and those from English-speaking
countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
