<HEADLINE> Spaniard Martinez, Corretja Bowed out of French Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Both Conchita Martinez and Alex
Corretja joined the exodus of seeds as they were stopped in the
fourth round of the French Open tennis tournament on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's Amanda Coetzer and Belgium qualifier Filip
Dewulf became the winners over the Spaniards on the red clay of
Roland Garros.
</P>
<P>
Coetzer, the 11th seed, won a three-set game over Martinez 6-7,
6-4, 6-3 while Dewulf upset eighth seed Corretja, one of the
pre-tournament favourites, 5-7, 6-1, 6-4, 7-5 on the centre court.
</P>
<P>
The win was the first for Coetzer against Martinez in their 11
meetings, which last two hours and 43 minutes.
</P>
<P>
"Before today I had never beaten her, I don't think I had even
taken a set from her."
</P>
<P>
Coetzer jumped to a 5-2 lead, before Martinez, the 1994
Wimbledon champion, stormed back to take a 6-5 lead and win the
set in one hour and 22 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Trailing 4-1 in the second, the 25-year-old South African broke
Martinez three times winning the next five games and the set.
</P>
<P>
The decisive set saw the two women trading breaks twice before
Coetzer finally controlled the court to end Martinez's bid for a
ninth consecutive semifinal appearance.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Dewulf made the big surprise by becoming the
first Belgian to reach a Grand Slam quarter-final.
</P>
<P>
Dewulf, ranked 122 in the world, clinched his most significant
win of his career in two hours 57 minute.
</P>
<P>
"I came here to play the qualifying and I'm in the
quarter-finals, it's totally unexpected," said Dewulf who failed
to advance beyond the second round in previous Grand Slam
events. 
</P>
</TEXT>
