<HEADLINE> Chinese Capital Adopting Unleaded Gasoline Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Starting today, over 300 gasoline
stations in Beijing's eight urban districts will stop selling any
gasoline that contains lead.
</P>
<P>
As of January 1, 1998, all local gas stations will sell
unleaded gasoline.
</P>
<P>
The move by the Beijing Municipal government is intended to
protect the quality of the air which has become polluted by
automobile exhaust. The number of motor vehicles in the city was
about 1.2 million at the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The China Petroleum Corporation has asked its refineries to
produce more unleaded gasoline for Beijing, and the local
government will penalize gasoline dealers who don't comply with
the policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
