<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Fail to Break Israel's Closure by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 1 (Xinhua) - The Palestinians failed to break
Israel's closure of their territories to secure economic autonomy
with the cancellation of the Palestinian Airlines first ever
commercial flight scheduled today to leave here for Al Arish,
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The cancellations, which also include Palestinian Airline's
flights between Al Arish and Saudi Arabia, Cyprus and Turkey, are
due to reasons "beyond our control," Director of the Palestinian
Civil Aviation Authority Fayez Zaidan told reporters Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Israel has imposed its closure to the Palestinian territories
now and then over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate that Israel closed the Palestinian
territories for 91 days in 1993, 71 days in 1994, 125 days in 1995
and 310 days in 1996.
</P>
<P>
During the closures, Palestinian-made products are unable to
move from Gaza to the West and vice versa. Palestinian goods also
find difficulty in reaching Jordanian, Egyptian, other Arab
states' and European markets.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli closure policy almost damaged the Palestinian
economy, incurring some 1.2 billion U.S. dollars loss so far and
giving rise to unemployment and poverty, according to statistics
from the Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have made repeated efforts to break the
closure and secure contacts with the outside world.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of a new Palestinian airport is just another
try of the Palestinians to procure a free way to somewhere beyond
the closure.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Palestinians planned to open an airport in Rafah
in the southern tip of the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
But the Israeli hard-line government refused the plan,
insisting on having full control over security and checks on
passengers and cargo at the new airport, something the
Palestinians refuse.
</P>
<P>
The dispute, which stems from Israeli claims of concern over
the possible smuggling of weapons and unauthorized people into the
Palestinian-ruled areas, have held up approval for the airport and
construction of a port in Gaza City for months.
</P>
<P>
Then Egypt agreed to build an airport in Al Arish for the
Palestinians, which stands at the border between Egypt and the
Gaza Strip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
