<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Voting Rate Rises in 2nd Round of French Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- More people participated in the second
round of the legislative election in France today than the last
round by mid-day, and the result of the election would be projected
in the evening after the voting.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac cast a vote this morning in
Sarran in the central department of Correze where he is a deputy
mayor, while Lionel Jospin, the Socialist Party leader and
Chirac's major rival, voted in Cintegabelle in the southwestern
department of Haute-Garonne.
</P>
<P>
The French Interior Ministry said that the participation rate by
12:00 today was 24.08 percent, 1.34 points higher than the 22.74
percent rate of the last round, held on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the participation rate rose from 18.77 percent to
21.04 percent in the first half of the day. But some departments
of the Paris region saw a slightly lower rate.
</P>
<P>
Both the left and right parties of France had appealed to the 31
percent of the voters who abstained in the first round to vote for
them in the second round.
</P>
<P>
The leftist Socialist-Communist bloc won the first round of the
legislative elections, forcing Chirac's central-right coalition
into a corner.
</P>
<P>
The French media said that it was difficult to predict which
side will win in the second round, but the leftist parties could
have better chances.
</P>
<P>
The 15 percent of the voters who voted for the extreme-right
National Front in the first round were believed to be playing a
decisive role in the second round. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
