<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Handicapped Orphans Celebrate Children's Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Today was the tenth birthday of Wei
Peng, a special day for the girl who lives in the Beijing
Children's Welfare Institute, because she received a "red scarf"
from a senior Chinese leader.
</P>
<P>
She wore a pink dress and sang and danced with other children
at the party held by the institute for the International
Children's Day.
</P>
<P>
But, when she came to the institute nine years ago, she had a
harelip. The institute sent her to a hospital for plastic surgery,
and today hardly any trace of her former problem can be found.
</P>
<P>
"I have a mother now, and this is her birthday present to me,"
she said holding up a parasol. "She's talking about a woman who
gives her pocket money every month and takes her out to play," her
teacher explained. "We call those women `assistant mothers'."
</P>
<P>
He Luli, vice-chairman of the National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference, who attended
the party, gave Wei Peng the young pioneer's red scarf.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Lin, Premier Li Peng's wife, who is deputy director of the
Chinese National Committee of Care for Children, brought a big
cake, and fruit and flowers to the institute on behalf of the
premier. Various units and people from Beijing gave 600,000 yuan
(about 72,000 US dollars) worth of food and gifts to the institute.
</P>
<P>
The institute has more than 400 orphans, 95 percent of whom
are handicapped, says Wang Chenguang, its director.
</P>
<P>
"Taking care of these handicapped children is a hard task," she
explains, "but our staff treat the children as their own." She
added that many teachers did not go home after the night shift but
stayed for the celebration today.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1984, the institute has a total floor space of
12,000 sq me and 500 beds for children under the age of 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
