<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Children's Day Co-operation In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Ten-year-old Liu Shigang is an
orphan who was one of the 100 children from poor families from
Beijing's poorer suburbs who were downtown today for a celebration
of International Children's Day.
</P>
<P>
They were invited by the municipal government and the women's
federation to the Great Hall of the People and Tian'anmen Square
where the usual solemnity was turned into a big playground for
children, with slides, games, puppet shows, and acrobatics. "I've
never seen so many wonderful things," Liu said.
</P>
<P>
What excited him even more was that he met a pal he had
corresponded with since the beginning of the year but had never
seen. Chen Shu, a boy of the same age, from one of the city's best
schools, had helped Liu with his studies through the mail.
</P>
<P>
Chen gave Liu some stationery and said: "We can continue our
correspondence and help each other with our studies."
</P>
<P>
The 100 children are outstanding students and have good moral
character, says Hu Zhaoguang, vice-mayor of Beijing. He says that
a well-educated younger generation is crucial to dealing with the
backwardness in remote mountainous areas, and the 100 children are
the future of those areas. "We hope that today's activities will
help the children love their hometowns and the motherland and will
encourage them to contribute to the development of their hometowns
when they grow up."
</P>
<P>
For Children's Day, all museums and parks in Beijing were free
to children.  
</P>
</TEXT>
