<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Supports Intervention in Sierra </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Secretary-General of the
Commonthwealth Organization, Emeka Anyaoku, on Saturday gave his
support to foreign intervention in Sierra Leone, local media reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Anyaoku told BBC that "If they (the coupists) persist in upsetting
an elected government, in inflicting looting and damage on the
country, I think every effort to restore order and legitimacy would be
welcomed".
</P>
<P>
With 1,300 soldiers of the west African peace-keeping force in
Liberia known as ECOMOG already in Freetown and more Ghanian troops
coming, the prospects of a military intervention further heightened
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi has said that his country and
the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) have the
responsibility to restore peace, stability and the legitimate
government of outsted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
As at Saturday, the evacuations of their nationals by the U.S,
France, Lebanon and other countries have nearly finished, the capital
of Sierra Leone is said to be in an uneasy calmness.
</P>
<P>
The leader of the May 25 coup, Major Paul Jonny Koromah, was
reportedly in negotiations with ECOWAS leaders for a peaceful
resolution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
He has also reportedly appealed to the United Nations for
protection against what appeared to be an imminent intervention,
which he has earlier vowed to resist.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Department of State Spokesman, John Dinger said on Friday
that the U.S. would oppose military intervention but would resort to
diplomatic efforts.
</P>
<P>
But reports reaching here said the U.S. charge d'affairs in
Freetown, Ann Wright has given support to military actions taken by
the ECOMOG forces led by Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
As African heads of states gather tomorrow in Harare, Zimbabwe, for
the 33rd summit of the Organization of African Unity, the issue of
Sierra Leone is expected to be the highlight of their discussions.
</P>
</TEXT>
