<HEADLINE> Egypt Tries to Narrow Palestinian-Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
said today that current Egyptian peace efforts are designed to
narrow the differences between the Palestinians and Israelis,
instead of exerting pressure on them.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview with the Cairo-based Voice of Arab
radio, Moussa said "Egypt is not required to urge the Palestinians
to accept something which contradicts their interests."
</P>
<P>
Moussa, who is now attending the Organization of African Union
(OAU) ministerial meeting in Harare, Zimbabwe, said the
Palestinian cause will be discussed during the 33rd African summit
slated for Monday in Harare.
</P>
<P>
He warned the current crisis facing the Mideast peace process
is very dangerous and urged an immediate solution to the peace
stalemate.
</P>
<P>
"Activating the stalled peace march requires a halt of Israeli
settlement activities, a sincere implementation of the signed
agreements, a respect to commitments and sound understanding of
the present regional conditions," the Egyptian top diplomat added.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks collapsed since mid-March when
Israel broke ground for a new Jewish settlement on disputed land
in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have made the resumption of talks conditional
on a halt to Israel's expansionary policy.
</P>
<P>
However, Israel has refused to stop the Har Homa construction
and instead proposed building a neighborhood for Arabs near the
Jewish housing project.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak said Saturday that Egypt is
not biased to the Palestinians but it supports the Palestinian
cause "because their land is in Israeli hands."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mubarak's political advisor Osama al-Baz left here
this morning for his fourth visit to Israel within 10 days to
continue Egypt's consultations with both the Palestinians and
Israelis to break the deadlock in the Mideast peace process.
</P>
</TEXT>
