<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Air Traffic Develops Fast in Uganda (by Cai Guozhong) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's air traffic has developed
fast in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Uganda Civil Aviation Authority (CAA) show that
arrivals at the country's sole international airport in entebbe near
kampala had increased from 110,100 passengers in 1991 to 300,000
passengers last year, representing a 172-percent rise.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the statistics indicate that domestic flights had
increased from 5,887 passengers in 1992 to 27,958 this financial
year, representing an over four-fold increase.
</P>
<P>
Cargo transport has also increased dramatically. Total cargo
through the airport had tripled between 1992 and 1995, from 6,700
tons to 20,000 tons. Turnover had increased from 400,000 dollars in
1991 to nine million dollars in 1996. And this year turnover will be
12.6 million dollars as CAA has predicted.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are 33 scheduled and regular airlines operating
at the airport as compared to 11 airlines in 1991. In 1982 when
political turmoil prevailed throughout the country, there were only
13 flights from Entebbe to a few foreign destinations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Uganda Airlines Corporation is to acquire by lease a
new plane of 737-300 series with a larger seating capacity of 118
passengers. The 737-200 series leased from Air Zimbabwe will be
returned to owners in November this year.
</P>
<P>
The above situation is attributed to various factors such as
stable political climate, the liberal economic policies, the
relaxation of immigration requirements and deliberate marketing
policies of the government and the CAA.
</P>
<P>
During the political turmoil from January 1971 to January 1986,
Uganda's economy was operating at a crawling speed. In 1986 when the
current government came to power, the country's economy started to
recover.
</P>
<P>
In order to maximise the size of the airport, the ACC is to repair
the old airport near the new one to handle cargo as well as domestic
flights so that the new terminal caters for international flights.
</P>
<P>
The CAA is making sure that with renovation taking place, the
design of the terminal will change to suit different tenants who will
be running business at the airport.
</P>
<P>
If the airport is further developed, it could serve as a
central and regional hub that would improve air transport across
the continent, the managing director of the CAA said here last
week with confidence. enditem

