<HEADLINE> GCC Calls for Turkish Withdrawal from Northern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministers of the six
Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states have called on Turkey to
withdraw its troops from northern Iraq and stop intervening in
the internal affairs of its neighbor.
</P>
<P>
The GCC foreign ministers, who ended their 63rd meeting in
Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, late Saturday night, expressed in a
statement their "profound" worry over the latest Turkish military
operations in northern Iraq, reports reaching here from
Riyadh said today.
</P>
<P>
"Based on our firm stance with regards to the necessity of
preserving Iraq's independence and sovereignty, we call on
Turkey to withdraw its troops from Iraqi territory," Qatar's
Foreign Minister Sheikh Hamad Bin Jassim Bin Jabr Al-Thani said
at the meeting's opening ceremony earlier Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was scheduled to be held on June 7-8 but later
moved up to May 31.
</P>
<P>
In their statement, the ministers also renewed their firm
stand on Iraq's full compliance with U.N. resolutions relating
to its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
They also condemned Iran's pursuit of the status quo policy
in the Islands of Abu Mousa and the Greater and Lesser Tunbs,
which they insisted constitutes a violation of the United Arab
Emirates' sovereignty over the islands and undermines regional
peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
On the results of the Iranian presidential elections, the
ministers hoped that the future would witness better ties
between the Gulf and Iranian people.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also voiced "profound" worry over the stalemate
in the peace process due to Israel's provocative policies, mainly
its settlement policy in the occupied territories.
</P>
<P>
They condemned the Israeli "illegitimate and irresponsible"
practices, urging Israel to honor the signed accords with the
Palestinians, halt the construction of new Jewish settlement and
adhere to Madrid's conference and the U.N. Security Council
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers also urged Israel to resume peace
negotiations with Syria from where they stopped and complete
withdrawal from the Golan Heights, south Lebanon and Western
Bekaa.
</P>
<P>
They hailed the efforts of Egypt and the European Union
toward pushing Middle East peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
