<HEADLINE> S. Africa's IFP Leader Backs Unity with ANC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Mangosuthu Buthelezi, top leader
of Inkatha Freedom Party (IFP), has expressed willingness to unite
with South Africa's ruling African National Congress (ANC), the local
daily Sunday Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
It would be "an ideal thing" if the two black parties get united,
Buthelezi said in an interview with reporters of the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi, also Minister of Home Affairs, made the
remarks when ANC National Chairman Jacob Zuma and his IFP counterpart
Ben Ngubane are in the forefront of a peace initiative which has seen
a significant thawing in relations between the major black parties.
</P>
<P>
The immediate aim of the present talks is to bring peace to Kwazulu
Natal Province and to put a stop to the bloody conflict between ANC
and IFP supporters that has claimed more than 14,000 lives since 1984.
</P>
<P>
Following the peace initiative, the level of violence has
decreased substantially and the parties can now explore restoring
their relations to their pre-1979 status, informed sources said.
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi colluded with the then-banned ANC to form IFP in 1975,
but cordial relations soured in 1979 when they differed on strategy,
and a bloody war ensued.
</P>
<P>
For now, the peace initiative is still at a sensitive stage,
but Buthelezi said he believed that the ANC and the IFP had been
driven apart by differences that were "not really necessary" and
which should not have led to a split.
</P>
<P>
Sources closed to the peace initiative sketched a scenario of
voluntary cooperation being forged at local level and extending to
national government.
</P>
<P>
This would result in the ANC and the IFP working together even
after 1999, during which a general election would be held in South
Africa, they said. enditem

