<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Sugar Industry Expects Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 1 (Xinhu) -- The South African sugar industry is
expecting a record 2.5 million ton crop this season and the
continuation of its export growth which earned the country 273 million
U.S. dollars last season, the local daily Sunday Tribune reported today.
</P>
<P>
The coming recovery will make the sugar industry the largest
agricultural exporter in terms of foreign exchange earnings, Andrew
Barr-Simm, the South African Sugar Association's export manager was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
While the 1996/97 crop did not fulfil its early promises, at 2.3
million tons, it was 50 percent above the average of the past four
years, and helps the sugar industry claw its way out the ravages
caused by an unprecedented drought, the industry sources said.
</P>
<P>
According to a market analyst, sugar prices in the world market are
reasonable and last season saw South Africa make use of its geographic
position to sell sugar to the West, the Far East and also to North
Africa.
</P>
<P>
From just three traditional markets, Japan, Korea and Israel,
South Africa has now expanded its exports to 31 countries, the
sources said. enditem

