<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Airline Suffers Losses From Engine Trouble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Cathay Pacific Airways, the
leading airline in Hong Kong, is expected to lose between 120
million to 150 million HK dollars (15 million to 19 million U.S.
dollars) because of the grounding of its A330-300 fleet.
</P>
<P>
Cathay canceled 143 flights over the past week when a
succession of in-flight engine shutdowns forced its 11 A330-300
jets grounded.
</P>
<P>
The airline's chairman, Peter Sutch, said the estimated cost
includes the loss of ticket revenue, costs of chartering aircraft
from other carriers and spending on accommodations for stranded
passengers.
</P>
<P>
He expected that all grounded aircraft would be flying again in
two weeks. The problem with the Trent 700 engines that power
A330-300s has been identified and replacement will start this
week, according to the chairman.
</P>
<P>
The same engine crisis also affected another Hong Kong-based
airline, Dragonair, which grounded its four A330-300 planes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970601.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big UK Companies Top Pollution List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Five of Britain's largest companies
become the worst polluters by illegally releasing thousands of
tons of toxic gases and dangerous chemicals into the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
ICI, Blue Circle, Castle Cement, Rhone-poulenc, and Coalite are
among the worst lawbreakers in an investigation list published by
The Sunday Times today.
</P>
<P>
Michael Meacher, the environment minister, criticized the
Environment Agency, which was set up last year to regulate
pollution in England and Wales, for failing to punish offenders
properly.
</P>
<P>
"I made it clear that I expect the agency to take a tougher
line on enforcement and prosecution in the future. I have been
advised that it is doing exactly this in the ICI case," he said.
</P>
<P>
The agency's data indicate that Britain's most poisonous plant
is ICI's Merseyside chemical factory at Runcorn.
</P>
<P>
The data show that since 1995 the Runcorn plant has broken the
law 472 times, sometimes releasing toxic chemicals into
neighboring communities.
</P>
<P>
Families living near such factories are reportedly more likely
to sustain chronic respiratory illness and are at greater risk of
lung cancer and leukaemia.
</P>
<P>
Medical studies of the health of residents living in the shadow
of plants run by the ICI, Blue Circle and Castle Cement also
suggest four times the usual rate of lung cancer and asthma among
women and children.
</P>
<P>
Last month the agency summoned senior ICI executives to a
special meeting. Ronald Hampel, the ICI chairman, admitted that
his company had been at fault and he regretted the incidents.
</P>
<P>
"From time to time there are human failings. I have made the
point to our businesses that this was unacceptable," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
