<HEADLINE> Egypt's Envoy Returns to Israel for Mediation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's
political advisor Osama al-Baz left here this morning for Israel
to continue Egypt's consultations with both the Palestinians and
Israelis to break the deadlock in the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
During his meetings with Israeli top officials, Baz will get
acquaint with Israel's stance toward the Palestinian side's
demands to restart the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He will also convey the Israel's reply to the Palestinian
National Authority.
</P>
<P>
Intensive Egyptian diplomatic efforts to revive the Mideast
peace process climaxed last Tuesday when Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak met with Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu in the
Egyptian Red Sea resort of Sharm el-Sheikh.
</P>
<P>
Baz has been shuttling between the two sides since Tuesday's
summit in a bid to bring Israel and the Palestinians back to the
negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
His trip came a day after two leading Palestinian negotiators
held consultations here Saturday on Egypt's efforts to save the
peace talks that collapsed when Israel began building Har Homa, a
Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Minister of Local government Saeb Erekat and
senior negotiator Hassan Asfour arrived here Friday night, the
same day the Palestinian leadership, during a weekly meeting in
Ramallah, voiced welcome and support for the Egyptian bid to
reactivate the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have made their return to the negotiating
table conditional on a halt of Israel's expansionary policy.
</P>
<P>
Egypt was floating a five-point plan to persuade the two sides
to the table, which includes a temporary halt of settlement
activities in Jerusalem and the West Bank, as well as the
resumption of Palestinian-Israeli security coordination.
</P>
<P>
In Gaza, Palestinian officials have declared their opposition
to a map reportedly being drafted by Netanyahu to give
Palestinians 40 percent of the West Bank lands in the final talks.
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu denied that he has decided on any such map.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has refused to stop the Har Homa construction and
instead proposed building a neighborhood for Arabs near the Jewish
housing project as well as other measures to ease the limitations
against the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Highlighting the severity of the two-month-old crisis, clashes
broke out Friday between Palestinians and Israeli soldiers in the
West Bank town of Bethlehem. Two were wounded when some 500
Palestinians marched to protest the death of a Palestinian
man in Israeli custody. 
</P>
</TEXT>
