<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 09:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Impose Heavy Fines on Traffic Violators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Traffic violators in Iran will face
heavy fines starting from June 7, the Persian daily Akhbora reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Deputy Interior Minister Gholamhossein Bolandiyan
announced Saturday that starting from next week, drivers who have
excessive speed, violate the left lane which belongs to the
incoming traffic, pass other cars on the right, or have defective
lights will have to pay five times more fines.
</P>
<P>
He said that fines for excessive speed, unlawful passing and
violating the incoming traffic lane will be increased from 10,000
rials (3.3 U.S. dollars) to 50,000 rials (16.66 dollars) and the
fines for defective lights will increase from 500 rials (0.16
dollars) to 2,500 rials (0.83 dollars).
</P>
<P>
The new measures are adopted after a recent study
sponsored by the Interior Ministry showed that the four types
of violations are major causes of accidents in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Iran reported an average of 36,000 traffic accidents per year,
ten times more than in other countries.
</P>
<P>
In last Iranian year (1995-96), Iran recorded 205,000
collisions for some 3 million cars. Around 5,000 people were
killed in traffic accidents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
