<HEADLINE> Israeli Peace Activists Stage Anti-Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of Peace Now activists
held a rally here Saturday night against the government's hardline
policy regarding the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators of Peace Now, one of the major Israeli peace
organizations supporting the Oslo Accords, marched from the Prime
Minister's Office to Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu's home in
Beit Hakerem, to mark a "year of failure" and symbolically to show
him the way to go home.
</P>
<P>
Some demonstrators carried placards with slogans reading: "Bibi
(the prime minister's other name) is destroying peace" and "Stop
building Har Homa," a new Jewish settlement in East Jerusalem
which has stalled the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks since March.
</P>
<P>
Speakers at the rally accused Netanyahu of neither achieving
peace nor security since he came to power following election
victory on May 29, 1996. On the contrary, they stated, a danger of
war with Arab neighbors appears to be increasing.
</P>
<P>
When the last speaker began to address the rally, power was all
of a sudden cut off. Peace Now blamed rightwing extremists for the
outage.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the major opposition Labor Party and left-wing
Meretz party are also planning to launch an anti-government
campaign, which will focus on the stalemate of the peace
process. 
</P>
