<HEADLINE> Banned Refrigerators Sold in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of refrigerators banned in the
"first world" because of their ozone depleting substances (ODS) are
finding their way into Zambian market, Sunday Times of Zambia reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Because of low importation costs the business is roaring in the
country, according to the local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The Environmental Council of Zambia (ECZ) is unable to control the
importation of these ice boxes because of absence of punitive
legislation.
</P>
<P>
A survey by the newspaper shows that second hand refrigerators and
compressors mostly from European countries are on sale with prices
ranging from 200,000 Kwacha (about 150 US dollars) to 500,000 Kwacha
(about 380 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Businessmen in Europe, who are just picking up the fridges from
people and shops at almost no cost at all, are making huge profits on
sale of the obsolete coolers, according to survey.
</P>
<P>
It is apparent that Africa has once again become a dumping ground
for such, a local fridge dealer complained.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted him also saying that the influx of the second
hand fridges has killed business for brand new ones which are ozone
friendly.
</P>
<P>
ODS producing refrigerators have been banned in most of the "first
world" countries which are signatories to the Vienna Convention and
Montreal Protocol signed in 1990.
</P>
<P>
But a special schedule for developing countries was put in place to
slowly phase out the ODS until July 1, 1999 wheh there will be a total
ban. enditem

