<DOCNO> XIE19970601.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Must Strive for Economic Unity: Salim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, Jnne 1 (Xinhua) -- African countries should put to
rest ''for good'' the notions of Afro-pessimism and work towards
economic integration as an African economic community, OAU
Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim has said.
</P>
<P>
The body, said Salim in an exclusive interview with the Sunday
Mail, faced new challenges and should remain as united as it had been
to surmount them.
</P>
<P>
These challenges included the laying down of the foundation of
economic integration and of solving the problems of socio-economic
transformation in most previously war-torn African countries like
Mozambique and Angola. The issue of conflict prevention, resolution
and management was still an area that needed closer attention and
could feature prominently during the summit, he said.
</P>
<P>
''We have been involved in all African conflicts. In the past it
was considered unthinkable to discuss internal conflicts, now it's
considered unacceptable when these are discussed when the oau is not
involved,'' said the 55-year-old former tanzanian prime minister.
</P>
<P>
On the economic front, he said, the African leaders should
form the long-awaited African economic community and the Harare
summit was expected to ratify the formation of the AEC. Already
44 countries had ratified the transformation and ''those who have
not will do so'', he said.
</P>
<P>
He said this demonstrated the level of political commitment from
the heads of state of Africa and the expected transformation would
see Africa playing a direct role on the international scene and move
away from being followers of old bodies like the European Community.
</P>
<P>
He said, ''Africa just has to put its act together. We have to
take the issue of economic integration with the seriousness it
deserves.''
</P>
<P>
Unity within the continental body had remained one of its
strongest points, he said.
</P>
<P>
''We need the unity and solidarity as we face the new challenges
of economic integration, that of refugees, that of democratisation,
the challenges of people refusing to be marginalised. It is African
people who can put to rest those new theorists of afro-pessimism,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed, ''in unity we have been able to achieve our political
freedom and in unity we shall be able to be a force to reckon with in
the international system.''
</P>
<P>
The OAU Secretary-General was reelected for a second term in June
1993. He was seeking reelection for his third and probably last term.
</P>
<P>
If reelected, Salim said, he would not only continue with
reforming the organisation to ensure the full use of the limited
resources but would also look at building a greater constituency for
the organisation. enditem

