<HEADLINE> Palestinian Airlines Fails to Launch Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 1 (Xinhua) - The Palestinian Airlines fails to
launch its first ever commercial flight scheduled today to leave
here for Al Arish, Egypt, leaving the Palestinians another
set-back in their efforts to break Israel's closure to their
territories.
</P>
<P>
The exact reasons for the cancellation, which happened as the
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been stalled for more
than two months, have not been disclosed yet.
</P>
<P>
"The indefinite postponement of the inaugural flight is due to
reasons beyond our control," director of the Palestinian Civil
Aviation Authority Fayez Zaidan told reporters Saturday.
</P>
<P>
All Palestinian Airlines flights between Al Arish and Saudi
Arabia, Cyprus, Turkey and other destinations of Egypt due to
start next month, have also been put back, the director said.
</P>
<P>
"We do not know when the problems preventing us from launching
these routes will be resolved," he added.
</P>
<P>
The cancellation of the flight is believed to be another
set-back in the efforts of the Palestinians to secure the autonomy
of their economy, which has lost some 1.2 billion U.S. dollars so
far due to Israel's closure of their territories.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian Airlines decided earlier to launch the routes
from Al Arish, near Egypt's border with the Gaza Strip, after
Israel refused to let them open a new airport in Rafah in the
southern tip of the strip.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli hardline government insists on having full
control over security and checks on passengers and cargo at the
new airport, something the Palestinians refuse.
</P>
<P>
The disputes, which stem from Israel's claims of concern over
the possible smuggling of weapons and unauthorized people into
the Palestinian self-ruled areas, have held up approval for the
airport and construction of a port in Gaza City for months.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian Airlines has two Fokker 50 planes donated by
the Netherlands. The planes carried Palestinian Muslims to the
annual pilgrimage in Mecca, Saudi Arabia, from Al Arish this year.
</P>
<P>
The Rafah airport was authorized under a 1995 autonomy accord,
and its opening is seen as a symbol of Palestinian ambitions to
sovereignty and a much-needed boost for the economic autonomy of
the territories, which now must export most of their goods via
Israel and have seen huge unemployment, decrease of income and
increasing poverty among the Palestinians due to the Israeli
closure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
