<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Accelerate Equitization Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam is to accelerate the
equitization process of state-owned enterprises, Vietnam News
Agency (VNA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The major acceleration steps to be taken by the government
include improvement of relevant laws and regulations and the
establishment of a stock market in the country.
</P>
<P>
The report said that equitization process of the enterprises
has proceeded "slowly" since it was initiated a decade ago. The
report attributed the reasons to people's unfamiliarity with the
concept, worries over losses, the hesitation of investors and the
unfavorable legal environment.
</P>
<P>
To date only 10 of the 150 businesses selected for pilot
equitization have completed the process, with five in Ho Chi Minh
city, the economic hub of the country.
</P>
<P>
The equitization, carried out as part of a plan to establish a
stock market in the country, is designed to attract more domestic
investment to help renovate equipment and management with the
ultimate aim of promoting economic development and boosting
business efficiency.
</P>
<P>
The report explained that unlike privatization, which means
selling all state assets to private buyers, equitization is the
transfer of part of assets via shares to workers, other businesses
and private buyers including foreigners.
</P>
<P>
In government terms, this process is called diversification of
ownership and the state holds some 30 percent of the shares.
</P>
<P>
Equitization has led to an annual growth rate of 56.9 percent
in turnover, 70.2 percent in profits, 98 percent in state-budget
contribution and 20 percent in employees' year-on-year incomes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970601.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast China Protecting Arable Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
Province has found administrative and economic ways to halt the
process of rapidly-shrinking arable land.
</P>
<P>
It is trying to keep the amount of arable land lost to economic
development annually to below 14,667 hectares, to maintain a
balance in land use.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning is China's oldest heavy industrial base and has a
population of 40 million, half of whom are urban residents, with
big demands for farm produce. But, a decade ago, 32,000 ha of
arable land was being lost annually, a process that would leave
almost nothing to cultivate after 100 years.
</P>
<P>
So, land administrative departments have put 333,333 ha of
farmland under protection, and do not allow any organizations to
touch it. Arable land production is estimated at 16 billion kg of
grain and enough vegetables and fruits to meet local demand.
</P>
<P>
The province also intensified wasteland reclamation over the
past decade and has recovered up 86,667 ha for farming.
</P>
<P>
The provincial People's Congress has also passed local land
laws parallel to the Law on Management of Land, which took effect
nationwide in 1986, and has set up special teams to enforce the
law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
