<HEADLINE> Shipbuilding Regulations In East Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Nanjing, the capital of Jiangsu
Province in East China, has set regulations to standardize its
rapidly-growing shipbuilding and ship repair industry.
</P>
<P>
The regulations say that those wanting to open shipbuilding or
ship repair businesses must get approval from communications
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The document also says that design, construction and reparation
of ships must comply with standards, technical requirements, and
rules of the State and certain international agreements. And ships
that fail to pass an examination can not leave the shipyard.
</P>
<P>
The document takes effect July 1, and is intended to prevent
the fast-growing industry from developing in an irregular way,
sources say.
</P>
<P>
Nanjing, which is on the Yangtze River, now has 15 shipbuilders
in its townships and 45 private companies in that business.
</P>
<P>
Because of the lack of regulations, problems and disputes over
quality and cost have arisen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
