<DOCNO> XIE19970601.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Africa with Promising Future But Grave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Latest statistics by the United
Nations African Economic Commission show that Africa registered
an annual GDP growth of 3.9 percent last year, as against two
percent in 1994 and 2.74 percent in 1995. 1996 was the first year
when the economic growth rate of Africa surpassed its population
growth rate.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, foreign trade of Africa also improved with the value
of exports increasing by 8.7 percent and the value of imports by
9.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has predicted that in the coming 10 years the
African economy will continue to grow at an annual average rate
of 3.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Africa is a vast continent with rich human and natural
resources for exploitation. It is the only potential market left
in the world.
</P>
<P>
However, Africa remains in poverty due to long-time colonial
rule in the past and the unjust and unreasonable political and
economic orders in the world. There are still unrests in some
countries in the continent, particularly in the Great Lakes
region. Outside forces are still trying to intervene in Africa's
affairs for their own interests. All these are grave hindrance to
its development.
</P>
<P>
Though African countries have made good achievements in
economic revitalization in recent years, the continent is still
far behind other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
Africa's trade value accounts for only two percent of the
world's total. From 1991 to 1995, direct investment from the
outside accounted for only two percent of the world total and
five percent of the total of developing countries. It stood at
4.5 billion US Dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Foreign debts of Africa grew from 328.7 billion US Dollars in
1995 to 340.5 billion US Dollars in 1996. Two thirds of the
people in the continent live in poverty. In addition, the
problems of refugees, unemployment, illiteracy and the spread of
diseases seriously restrict developments of African countries.
</P>
<P>
If it is said that the struggle in the 1960s for national
independence from colonial rule was the first wakening of Africa,
the present common drive for stability and development is the
second wakening of the continent.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the imminent 33rd OAU summit will surely
further promote peace, stability and development in the
continent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970601.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
