<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest China Province Revitalizing State Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Gansu Province in northwest China
is on the road to revitalizing its stagnant state-owned sector, so
far reducing losses of the 1,454 state industrial enterprises that
have independent accounting systems by 8.13 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
The state enterprises, which account for 23 percent of the
province's total industrial businesses, produced 77 percent of the
industrial profit and tax last year, thanks to improved management.
</P>
<P>
The province introduced the modern enterprise system to 32
selected state enterprises, whose net assets worth 16.95
billion yuan make up one-fifth of the province's state-invested
capital.
</P>
<P>
Preferential policies such as the switch from appropriations to
loans, helped reduce the average liability-asset ratio of the
pilot enterprises from 64.2 percent to 61.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Share-holding reform is going strong in the province. And six
of its state enterprises have issued shares at the Shanghai and
Shenzhen bourses, with a total capital stock worth nearly 500
million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Gansu reorganized 1,001 of its enterprises, involving 2.4
billion yuan worth of assets, and re-located 82,700 of the firms'
workers.
</P>
<P>
The Lanzhou Walking Tractor Plant has increased its production
capacity from 100 million yuan to 500 million yuan by merging
three and half enterprises in three years, to become the largest
of its kind in northwest China.
</P>
<P>
The province has allowed more autonomy to small enterprises,
and transformed 152 of them by issuing shares, being leased, or
selling at auction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
