<HEADLINE> HK-Beijing Relay Kicks-Off to Mark HK Handover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 1 (Xinhua) -- More than 350 runners rushed off
the starting line at the Wanchai Sports Ground here this morning,
marking the beginning of a month-long relay from Hong Kong up to
the Chinese capital, Beijing, to mark Hong Kong's reunification
with its motherland, China.
</P>
<P>
Leading the starting squad at the starting ceremony were
China's Asian record holder in men's triple jump Zou Zhenxian and
Hong Kong's Wushu master Ng Siu Ching, who won Hong Kong's sole
gold medal at the East Asian Games in Pusan, South Korea in May.
</P>
<P>
Among other participants of the super-long relay are some ace
athletes or former stars from both Hong Kong and China's mainland,
including China's table tennis world champion and Olympic gold
medalist Deng Yaping and her title-winning teammates, world record
holder and long-distance runner Wang Junxia, former women's high
jump world record holder Zheng Fengrong and former Asian and world
champion walker Xu Yongjiu.
</P>
<P>
The starting ceremony is to be followed by a cross-over by some
50 runners at the Huanggang Check Point of Shenzhen and a ceremony
in the city's indoor stadium later today.
</P>
<P>
The relay will have a total of 11 stages at Hong Kong and
Chinese cities of Guangzhou, Changsha, Wuhan, Shanghai, Nanjing,
Zhengzhou, Jinan and Tianjin before reaching the destination of
the relay, Beijing, on June 30, where a grand ceremony has been
scheduled at the Workers Stadium.
</P>
<P>
Chinese officials of the local governments, celebrities and
representatives of athletes from clubs subordinate to the Hong
Kong Amateur Athletic Association (HKAAA) will join in the relay
at various stages.
</P>
<P>
The event was jointly organized by the Chinese Athletic
Association and the HKAAA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
