<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Africa with Promising Future But Grave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Du Zhenfeng and Zhu Shixiang)
</P>
<P>
HARARE, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The 33rd summit of the Organization
of African Unity (OAU) will be held in Harare, capital of
Zimbabwe, on June 2-4.
</P>
<P>
There are three major topics to be discussed at the summit,
namely, further maintenance and enhancing of peace and stability
in the continent, economic and social revitalization and
development, and election of the secretary general of the
organization for the next term.
</P>
<P>
Since the last summit, which was held early July, 1996,
political and economic developments in the continent have been
getting better in general.
</P>
<P>
In the past year, the OAU and sub-regional organizations have
made their contributions to strive for and maintain stability in
the continent.
</P>
<P>
In May, OAU Secretary General Salim Ahamed Salim reiterated
that the OAU will continue all its efforts to maintain peace and
stability in Africa on the basic principle that African affairs
are settled by the Africans themselves.
</P>
<P>
The peace process in Angola has been successful and
satisfactory. Liberia has embarked on the road to national
reconciliation. Major warring factions in Somalia have reached a
peace agreement. The Central African Republic has solved in a
peaceful way its political crisis resulted from a military
mutiny. And, the presidents of the Sudan and Uganda have agreed
to stop hostilities and cooperate for national development.
</P>
<P>
In the political and economic ups and downs since the end of
the cold war in the world arena, African countries have made
efforts to try to find their own ways for economic and social
developments.
</P>
<P>
They have come to a common view that the Africans should rely
mainly on themselves to build political systems in accordance
with Africa's historical and cultural traditions in the interest
of state stability and national unity so as to create a peaceful
and stable political environment for economic development.
</P>
<P>
In a comparatively suitable political and economic environment
in the continent and the world at large, African countries have
further adjusted their policies so as to attract more
investments, intensify economic cooperation and integration in
the continent and strengthen economic and trade exchanges with
the rest of the world. Their efforts have brought in success.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970601.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Government Asked to Ban Tobacco Advertising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government has been
asked to ban any form of tobacco advertising in the country where
over one- third of the population have the habit of smoking.
</P>
<P>
A memorandum against tobacco advertising along with 100,000
people's signatures was handed over to Health Minister Radha
Krishna Mainali on Saturday when a program was held here to mark
the World No-Tobacco Day, the local press said today.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum, submitted by a local anti-smoking organization,
requested the government to immediately stop any tobacco
advertisement in the governmental media.
</P>
<P>
Advertisements relating to tobacco mainly are mainly carried by
state-run media in Nepal, the memorandum said, adding that the
glamorization of cigarette smoking has made a negative impact and
helped increase the number of tobacco consumers.
</P>
<P>
Nepal has more than 50,000 cancer patients among its population
of 20 million and some 80 percent of the patients are tobacco
victims, a health expert said at the program.
</P>
<P>
About 7.1 million people in Nepal above the age of 15 are
smokers and the smoking rates among men and women are 65 and 60
percent respectively, according to official estimates.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Mainali disclosed on the occasion that steps
have been taken to discourage the habit of smoking and remove
tobacco advertisements from the governmental media.
</P>
<P>
He also promised to enhance a publicity campaign through the
official media to create people's awareness against tobacco and
offset the effect of tobacco advertisements.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
