<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Electronic Tagging Asked to Reduce Prison Overcrowding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Italy's chief anti-mafia prosecutor
today appealed for the introduction of electronic tagging to
relieve prison overcrowding.
</P>
<P>
Piero Luigi Vigna argued that being electronically tagged is
better than being held in a 16-inmate jail cell.
</P>
<P>
"In Italy, when we talk about electronic tagging, there are
people who reply that it is worse than being in prison because it
limits freedom, as if being in a cell with 15 others was some kind
of liberty," Vigna told a conference in Florence.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Italy's Prison Doctors' Association warned
of an explosive situation in the country's prisons, with more
than 50,000 inmates held in accommodation built for 32,500.
</P>
<P>
Vigna said that as well as reducing overcrowding, tagging could
bring down the cost of looking after prisoners.
</P>
<P>
"For some kinds of crimes, society ought to be able to accept
the risks of semi-liberty," Vigna said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
