<HEADLINE> Crimes Rise in Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Increased crimes of
assassinations, burglaries and stickups in the first five months
have made Costa Ricans feel more insecure, according to an opinion
poll.
</P>
<P>
Police authorities noted that the higher insecurity is due to
a change in the strategy of the criminals, who now attack
videoclubs, restaurants, universities, drug stores, suppliers and
houses.
</P>
<P>
Women and old people feel most insecure because they are most
unprotected from criminal attacks, according to the poll.
</P>
<P>
Linnette Saborio, head of the organization of judicial
investigation, proposed to increase interpolice cooperation in
combatting organized crimes.
</P>
<P>
Arms and drug smuggling, bank and business hold-ups, and car
thefts are the most common crimes in Costa Rica. 
</P>
</TEXT>
