<DOCNO> XIE19970601.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China aims to Improve Trade with Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- China expects to work with
Britain's new government to enhance bilateral trade, reported
today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to discuss ways of further developing bilateral trade
and economic relations with our counterparts in the United
Kingdom," the paper quoted Hu Chusheng, a senior official from the
Foreign Trade Ministry, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Sino-UK Trade and Economic co-operation Joint
Commission met for the first time in London. The commission is
intended to promote two-way trade.
</P>
<P>
It consists of three sub-groups in power, chemicals and
aerospace.
</P>
<P>
Britain was the last country in Europe to form such a
commission with China.
</P>
<P>
According to Chinese statistics, two-way trade grew steadily in
the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Sino-British trade volume increased 9.1 percent from the same
period last year to 1.15 billion US dollars in the first three
months. It helped bolster Britain's position as China's second
largest trade partner in European Union.
</P>
<P>
China's exports soared 16.8 percent to 721 million US dollars,
while imports from Britain fell 1.8 percent to 425 million US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade volume surpassed five billion US dollars for
the first time in 1996, the paper said. Trade between the two
economies has proceeded smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Britain is the largest EU investor in China. By the end of
1996, China had 1,800 British-funded enterprises, involving 11.93
billion US dollars contractual funds and 3.5 billion US dollars
actually invested.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Britain ranked third among EU countries in trade
volume with China. Bilateral trade was 5.08 billion US dollars. Of
that, China's exports were 3.2 billion US dollars and its imports
were 1.88 billion US dollars, Chinese statistics indicate.
</P>
<P>
Although trade volume has been growing, the volume does not
suit the economic power of the two nations, Beijing-based trade
experts said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Britain should try to expand its technology exports to
China, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970601.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Dam in Myanmar State Put Into Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The newly built Zawgyi dam in Shan
State of Myanmar has been put into service to boost agricultural
production in the area.
</P>
<P>
The dam, which was inaugurated on Saturday, will irrigate
44,550 hectares of land, enabling local farmers to grow more crops
than ever before, the official paper The New Light of Myanmar
reported today.
</P>
<P>
A hydropower project of the dam, which is scheduled to be
completed by September, will generate 12 megawatts of electricity.
</P>
<P>
The earth dam is 43.5 meters high and 765 meters long, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 78 dams have been completed in the country since
1988, irrigating more than 486,000 hectares of farmland.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's gross domestic product registered a 5.8-percent
increase in 1996-97, in which agricultural production went up by
3.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The country's rice export was recorded at 271,900 tons in 1996,
 compared with 637,100 tons in the previous year, according to
official figures.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
