<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Sets Tough Demands for Serbia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, May 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright today warned that the United States would not ease
sanctions on Serbia unless the former Yugoslav republic improves
the situation in the volatile Kosovo and stop backing Bosnian
Serbs.
</P>
<P>
At a 90-minute meeting with Serbian President Slobodan
Milosevic, Albright said that Serbia should also take actions in
punishing Bosnian war crimes, returning refugees and improving
political and media freedom before expecting any change in outside
pressure.
</P>
<P>
Albright, on a whirlwind tour of the three Balkan signatories
to the 1995 Dayton peace accord, said at a news conference after
the meeting that Serbia was "at a fork in the road."
</P>
<P>
If Serbia fails to meet U.S. demands, she said, "the United
States would make sure they are not part of the dynamic trend that
was taking place in Europe and that they would be left far behind."
</P>
<P>
Making clear the U.S. determination to "fully support Serbia's
efforts to build democracy and an open society," Albright said her
country will give Serbia 5 million U.S. dollars this year to
encourage the nation's democratization and independent press.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Milosevic expressed the desire to
normalize relations with the United States and sought U.S. backing
in its bid to regain its positions in the United Nations and other
international institutions.
</P>
<P>
However, Albright insisted the premise is Serbia's full
observance of the U.S.-brokered Dayton pact to end the 43-month
Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
"I made clear to President Milosevic that it now was up to him
if there would be steps toward normalization," she told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Describing her talks with Milosevic as "probably the toughest
meeting" she has had with any president, Albright said she urged
Milosevic to help bring war criminals to justice who were indicted
by the war crimes Tribunal in The Hague, the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic told reporters after the meeting that their talks
were very open. "I am certain that we will achieve better and
better progress as regards the questions we discussed and
normalize our relations step by step," he said.
</P>
<P>
Later today Albright met representatives of Serbian opposition
parties and their media.
</P>
<P>
Albright had met Croatian President Franjo Tudjman earlier in
Zagreb and will fly to Sarajevo tomorrow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
