<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas RMB Banks to Pay Income, Business Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Foreign banks will be subject to
national taxation treatment when they deal in local currency, but
they will continue to be eligible for tax incentives for their
foreign currency operations, reported today's China Daily
(Business Weekly).
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a Ministry of Finance official as saying that
like domestic banks, foreign banks selected for the renminbi pilot
must pay 33 percent income tax and eight percent business tax.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, favorable tax treatment for overseas banks' foreign
currency business remains unchanged; they continue to pay a 15
percent income tax and are exempt from the business tax for five
years.
</P>
<P>
"The move aims to standardize the tax system, unify taxation
policies and promote fair play on the financial market," the
official said.
</P>
<P>
It is practical to give foreign banks different tax treatment
because they are required to set distinct accounts for their yuan
and foreign currency businesses.
</P>
<P>
The separate tax treatment provides a way to continue tax
incentives as well as bring foreign banks in line with domestic
banks, moving forward the unification of China's tax policies.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, foreign financial institutions grew quickly in
China. by the end of 1996, foreign companies had 156 operational
financial institutions for foreign currency businesses in 17
cities.
</P>
<P>
With the nation's deepened reforms and winder opening, more
foreign banks are eager to gain licences to deal in renminbi.
</P>
<P>
Nine foreign-funded banks have been approved to operate in yuan
in Shanghai"s Pudong New Area.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
