<HEADLINE> Program to Help Poor Students Given Trademark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The name of a program to help
drop-outs return to school has been put under the protection of
intellectual property rights (IPR), government sources said
recently.
</P>
<P>
"Project Hope" has been officially registered at the State
Administration for Industry and Commerce for a trademark -- the
first time a charitable program in China has received IPR
protection.
</P>
<P>
The trademark as well as relevant images will be used by the
China Youth Development Foundation, the initiator of the Project
Hope.
</P>
<P>
Other organizations and personnel are prohibited from using the
name of "Project Hope" to engage in money-raising activities, a
program executive said.
</P>
<P>
The program, launched in 1989, has helped 1.5 million children
in poverty-stricken areas return to school by collecting one
billion yuan (120 million US dollars) from the public. 
</P>
