<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Treaty Marks Normalization of Russia-Ukraine Ties: Statement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Russia and Ukraine are normalizing
relations by signing the Treaty of Friendship, Cooperation and
Partnership, says a joint declaration issued today by Russian
President Boris Yeltsin and Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma.
</P>
<P>
The treaty signed today in Kiev would put the bilateral
relations on a sound footing, the declaration said.
</P>
<P>
Both presidents emphasized that Russia and Ukraine should shape
their relationship on the principle of equality, mutual respect to
each other's sovereignty and territorial integrity, said the
document.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin praised Ukraine for becoming a non-nuclear nation, and
restated that Moscow will ensure Ukraine's safety according to an
agreement signed by the United States, Russia and Ukraine on
January 14, 1994.
</P>
<P>
Under that agreement, the United States and Russia would
guarantee Ukraine's security because the former Soviet republic
pledged to give up its nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and Kuchma warmly applauded the efforts of both
countries in resolving the dispute over the division of the Black
Sea Fleet. The resolution to the Black Sea Fleet is the key to the
normalization of relations between Russia and Ukraine, the
declaration said.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two countries had been standoffish as
both claimed the fleet and its main base Sevastopol after the
collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991.
</P>
<P>
After two years of quarreling, Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin came to Kiev Wednesday and signed three agreements on
the division of the Black Sea Fleet.
</P>
<P>
The issue was finally settled with Moscow officially
recognizing Sevastopol as Ukrainian territory and leasing the
naval base for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents expressed their satisfaction with the
arrangement of the fleet issue, saying it will fortify regional
security.
</P>
<P>
The two countries vowed to cooperate in international
affairs. Both sides stressed the importance of strengthening the
role of the United Nations and stood for the establishment of a
common European security package for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to develop close political, economic and
social relations between members of the Commonwealth of
Independent States, the joint declaration said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and Kuchma also hoped to expand economic links between
the two countries. They vowed to implement the free trade accord
between them.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents have plans to encourage mutual investment,
construct cross-border transport routes, establish trans-national
consortia and expand cooperation on the space industry,
agriculture and nuclear energy, the document said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said the treaty left no problems whatsoever for the
future ties between the two countries as it covered cooperation in
almost all aspects.
</P>
<P>
However, the treaty doesn't mean that Moscow and Kiev can
foresee a period of honeymoon after Yeltsin returns to the Kremlin
from Kiev.
</P>
<P>
Although the treaty said neither side should sign any treaty
against the other side with a third party and neither side should
allow its territory to be used to threaten the security of the
other side, they hold contrary views on relations with NATO.
</P>
<P>
Russia openly opposes NATO's eastward expansion while Ukraine
believes that an enlarged NATO will harm no one, but create a more
stable Europe.
</P>
<P>
Observers believe that the difference would last for some
time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970601.0154 </DOCNO>
