<HEADLINE> Thai Army Chief Urges Border Talks With Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Thai Army Commander-in-Chief Gen.
Chettha Thanajaro has called for talks between Thailand and
Myanmar to solve their dispute over an islet on their border.
</P>
<P>
The border dispute between Thailand and Myanmar could be
avoided if both sides agreed to consult each other over border
issues affecting them, the local press today quoted Chettha as
saying Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Chettha said the latest dispute over Myanmar's dredging of the
Moei River would have been unlikely to occur if both sides had
held talks to clear up the matter first.
</P>
<P>
An islet has been created in the Moei River, which forms the
border between the two countries, because of a change in the
river's course, forcing the river further into Myanmar's land. And
Myanmar was reportedly dredging the river in an effort to restore
the river to its original position.
</P>
<P>
Chettha said Thailand and Myanmar, both of which consider the
banks of the Moei River their border lines, should consult with
each other if any side wanted to do anything beyond the river
bank.
</P>
<P>
he said there would be no further border problem if both sides
followed the proposed rule.
</P>
<P>
Chettha said he would soon seek a meeting with Myanmar Army
Commander-in-Chief Gen. Maung Aye to create more understanding on
border problems.  
</P>
