<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Strengthen Iodized Salt Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government set to build
more than 100 iodized salt production sites nationwide and finally
form an overall production capacity of eight million tons in an
effort to eliminate iodine deficiency disorders (IDD) in the
country by 2000.
</P>
<P>
China's State Planning Commission has approved the iodized salt
project last November, which was estimated to cost 980 million
yuan, including a loan of 27 million US dollars provided by the
World Bank, a loan of 190 million yuan from China's State
Development Bank, and 190 million yuan paid by local salt
administrations.
</P>
<P>
According to Dong Zhihua, general manager of China Salt
Corporation, the year 1997 is of pivotal importance for the
project. All salt administrations nationwide are required to speed
up the implementation of the project and the salt monopoly.
</P>
<P>
China is a country with high occurrence of IDD. According to
officials with the Ministry of Health, some 450 million Chinese
people live in iodine-deficiency areas, taking more than 40 percent
of the world's total.
</P>
<P>
Of the 10.17 millions mentally-retarded people in China, around
80 percent are victims of iodine-deficiency. Some six million
infants are born in China's iodine-deficiency regions a year, of
which one million may be affected by the problem.
</P>
<P>
Early in 1994, the Chinese government has approved regulations
to eliminate IDD before 2000 and set concrete targets in the
regard. The legal document promulgated that not only all edible
salt must be iodized, but also all salt used by food processing
and animal husbandry should be iodized.
</P>
<P>
China Salt Corporation is empowered to issue licenses on
production, wholesales and transport of all edible
salt. Non-iodized salt sellers should be punished in accordance
with the same rules on counterfeit drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
Data from China Salt Corporation indicated that China last year
produced 6.06 million tons of iodized salt.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970601.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> MFN Status Should Become Permanent, Says Trade Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 1 (Xinhua) -- A top Chinese trade official has
urged the United States to clear hurdles over most favored nation
(MFN) status to provide a permanent anchor to growing business
contacts between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily reported Chinese Vice-foreign Trade
Minister Sun Zhenyu as saying that the United States should
encourage bilateral trade and investment by permanently settling
the MFN issue.
</P>
<P>
Washington reviews MFN status annually, casting a pall of
uncertainty over the prospect of Sino-US business.
</P>
<P>
"China has mutual unconditional MFN arrangements with all
trading partners that have trade agreements with it except the
United States which, proceeding from its domestic law, has
insisted on the annual review," Sun said, "It goes against the
interests of both countries."
</P>
<P>
Sun said MFN was essentially a basic, normal treatment between
any two trading partners. "It should not be mistaken as an
one-sided arrangement."
</P>
<P>
"The cancellation of MFN is a double-edged sword that hurts not
only China, but US middle-and lower-income consumers, as well as
US investors in China."
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong will be hurt as a free trade and world financial
center, he said.
</P>
<P>
Sun noted the US had become China's second largest trading
partner by 1996 with a bilateral trade volume of 42.8 billion US
dollars. US direct investment in China amounted to 14 billion US
dollars and involved more than 20,000 projects. This made the
United States the second largest foreign investor in China.
</P>
<P>
"If the US provides permanent MFN and further relaxes tech
export control to China, Sino-US economic co-operation will go
forward,"Sun said.
</P>
<P>
He said China's total import from 1997 to 2000 would surpass
700 billion US dollars, creating a huge market for foreign firms.
</P>
<P>
"For construction in energy, transportation and
telecommunications, we need to purchase at least 100 billion US
dollars of technology and equipment each year (until 2000)," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome US businesses to compete in the Chinese market," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
