<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sunken Warship to Be Salvaged in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 1 (Xinhua) -- China has begun salvage work of a
cruiser named "Zhiyuan," which was attacked by Japanese bombers
and sank in the Yellow Sea of northern China at the end of the
last century.
</P>
<P>
A ceremony was held recently on Dalu Island in northeast
China's Liaoning Province, marking the beginning of the
preparatory work for raising the sunken warship.
</P>
<P>
During the Sino-Japanese War (1894-1895), launched by Japan
to invade China, the Chinese navy of the imperial Qing government
suffered heavy losses, including the sinking in the Yellow Sea of
four warships bought from western countries.
</P>
<P>
Captain Deng Shichang, who went down with the Zhiyuan, has
become a household name in China over the past 100 years, and his
story was the subject of a popular film.
</P>
<P>
The province has conducted a series of maritime surveys on the
sunken cruiser, which reportedly rests on the bed of the sea 16.9
kilometers southwest from Dalu Island.
</P>
<P>
The warship suffers from heavy rust damage, and has accumulated
large amounts of sand, according to the China State Shipbuilding
Corporation, which is responsible for the salvage project.
</P>
<P>
"It will be a hard nut because the salvage work can only be
carried out from May to August," said a representative from the
corporation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
