<HEADLINE> Anti-Smoking Campaign Launched in Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rica's Social Security Fund
(CCSS) and Education Ministry will launch an anti-smoking campaign
in the next two months.
</P>
<P>
The campaign is designed to counteract the cigarette producers'
publicity promoting tobacco consumption among young people,
announced the Costa Rican authorities today.
</P>
<P>
Cigarrette producers spend 1.24 million U.S. dollars a year on
cigarette publicity in Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
CCSS medical administrator Julieta Rodriguez said that
cigarette producers have developed an aggressive plan to conquer
the younger population.
</P>
<P>
She noted that selling cigarettes with an allegedly low content
of nicotine and tar is another way to attract more consumers.
</P>
<P>
The two institutions will develop an education program and
publish an publication titled "Tobacco, the Epidemic of the 21st
Century" to educate all the students, said the government official.
</P>
<P>
According to data from the Institute for Alcoholism and
Pharmaco-Dependency, 35 percent of Costa Ricans from 12 to 70
years old have smoking habit and many of them started smoking
before 16.
</P>
<P>
The CCSS spends 3.25 million dollars a year to treat
smoking-related illnesses including cancers. enditem
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
