<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liu Yong and Ge Fei Starts Chinese Gold Rush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GLASGOW, Scotland, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Liu Yong and Ge Fei
started a Chinese gold rush when they won the mixed doubles of the
world badminton championships here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Sudirman Cup winner China also has two more gold medals
ensured, with a possible fourth in the men's singles.
</P>
<P>
Liu and Ge, both 21 years old, beat Denmark's Jens Erikson and
Marlene Thomsen 15-5, 16-17 and 15-4 in the final.
</P>
<P>
They said they had not expected to win the world title, but had
much confidence before the championships.
</P>
<P>
"But we were too eager to win that last point when we led 14-12
in the second game. In the third game we lowered our expectation
and fought point by point," Ge said after the match.
</P>
<P>
Ge, who will team up with Gu Jun in the women's doubles
semifinals against another Chinese pair, is the only shuttler who
has the hope to win two golds here.
</P>
<P>
In the men's singles, China's Sun Jun vanquished 31-year-old
Denmark's Olympic champion Poul-Erik Hoyer-Larsen 15-7, 14-17,
15-9 to meet another Dane Peter Rasmussen in the final.
</P>
<P>
Sun, the former world junior champion, said he knew he could
win even before the match began.
</P>
<P>
"I expected to win. I held a 2-1 record over him before the
match and I knew I could win."
</P>
<P>
Rasmussen, who never beat Arbi in the past four encounters
since 1995, rallied from one set down to gain a 9-15, 15-9 and
15-2 victory in 76 minutes.
</P>
<P>
"Actually I didn't expect to win. His attacks are very
good... I just played relaxed. If you are too tense, you cannot
play your normal game," said Rasmussen after the match.
</P>
<P>
In two Chinese-only women's singles semi-finals, defending
champion Ye Zhaoying beat Wang Chen to meet compatriot Gong
Zhichao, who defeated teammate Han Jingna.
</P>
<P>
Sunday's final will be the second time in two months after All
England Open that Ye meets Gong, who sailed into the semi-final
here by beating Indonesian badminton queen Susi Susanti.
</P>
<P>
In women's doubles semi-finals, China's Tang Yongshu and Qin
Yiyuan ousted second seed Rosiana Zelin and Eliza 11-15, 15-11 and
15-9.
</P>
<P>
They will meet world number one pair Ge Fei and Gu Jun, who
defeated fellow countrywomen Qian Hong and Liu Lu 15-3, 15-3.
</P>
<P>
In a rematch of the Olympic men's doubles final, Yap Kim Hock
and Cheah Soon Kit of Malaysia took sweet revenge by winning
against Olympic champions Rexy Mainaky and Ricky Subagja 15-9,
2-15, 15-12.
</P>
<P>
The only Indonesian hope for a medal here is Budiarto Sigit and
Candra Wijaya, who in turn evaporized South Korean's only medal
hope Lee Dong Soo and Yoo Yong Sung with a 15-11, 15-11 victory in
the other men's doubles semi-final. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
