<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Georgia Has No Plan to Join NATO: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Georgian Foreign Minister Irakly
Menagarishvili said today that his country has no plan to apply
for NATO membership soon but welcomes a closer cooperation with
the western alliance.
</P>
<P>
While dismissing the prospects that Georgia would consider a
bid for NATO membership in the near future, Menagarishvili told
reporters that the Georgian leadership places emphasis on
developing ties with the 16-nation bloc under its Partnership for
Peace Program.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Georgian leaders repeatedly said that the enlargement
of the Council of Europe was more important than NATO's eastward
expansion, because the 37-nation council plays a greater role in
guaranteeing stability and fostering economic development in the
outer Caucasian nations.
</P>
<P>
Georgia, a former Soviet Republic on the Black Sea between
Russia and Turkey, joined the Partnership for Peace Program in
1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
