<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970601.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Krajicek Storms Out in French Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Wimbledon champion Richard Krajicek
joined the lengthy list of men's seeded casualties when Patrick
Rafter and Mark Woodforde ensured the best Australian showing at
the French Open since 1969 here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Rafter enjoyed a 6-3, 4-6, 6-4, 6-2 success over Krajicek, a
result which left the Dutch sixth seed so gisgusted he refused to
appear for his post-match press conference and was fined 2,000
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Woodforde, ranked 79 in the world, than guaranteed an
all-Australian fourth round meeting with a convincing 6-4, 7-6,
6-3 victory over 11th seed Albert Costa.
</P>
<P>
With their respective victories, Rafter and Woodforde joined
compatriot Mark Philippoussis among 10 unseeded names in the last
16.
</P>
<P>
Although moody Chilean Marcelo Rios, seeded seventh, steamed
past Arnaud Boetsch in straight sets, the presence of just six
seeds in the last 16, one short of the record low set in 1994,
suggests the title is as wide open as many predicted beforehand.
</P>
<P>
Those, however, who felt the men's event would almost certainly
be an all-Spanish affair have been proved dramatically wrong.
</P>
<P>
Neither Woodforde or Philippoussis have ever progressed this
far in Paris and there has not been an Australian in the
quarter-finals for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
But after a week of constant sunshine, the red Parisian clay is
playing faster than normal and, of the foremost claycourt experts,
only Rios and the Spanish duo of Alex Corretja and Sergi Bruguera
remain.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Yevgeny Kafelnikov is still lurking in the
top half of the draw but the most significant fourth round
encounter in the bottom half looks set to be the showdown between
former champions Michael Chang and Bruguera.
</P>
<P>
Chang disposed of his third successive French opponent when
Stephane Simian retired with a groin strain at 5-2 in the second
set, and looks in an increasingly determined mood.
</P>
<P>
South African 13th seed Wayne Ferreira did not even make it on
court for his third round match against Petr Korda of the Czech
Republic.
</P>
<P>
Ferreira twisted an ankle in practice on Friday, allowing Korda
to book his first French Open fourth round berth since reaching
the final in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The top women were all involved in a succession of mis-matches
as they progressed to the last 16 without dropping a set or, in
some cases, breaking into a sweat.
</P>
<P>
Martina Hingis, the women's world number one, was arguably the
most impressive, flattening her teenage rival Anna Kournikova 6-1,
6-3 to maintain her unbeaten record this year.
</P>
<P>
Kournikova was powerless against the variety of Hingis's
strokes, holding out for only 42 minutes in what had been billed
as a showdown between two potential champions of the next
millennium.
</P>
<P>
Hingis will be back in action on Sunday against 16th seed
Barbara Paulus of Austria while Monica Seles is due to face Mary
Pierce, the sole French survivor.
</P>
<P>
Sixth seed Arantxa Sanchez Vicario, who beat Dominique Van
Roost of Belgium, meets Natasha Zvereva who downed 14th seed
Brenda Schultz-McCarthy 7-6, 6-4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
