<HEADLINE> Brief Latin American Cultual News (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The following are news related
to the culture, artistic, and entertainment events that occurred
in Latin America in the last few days:

Mexico Has Many Mankind Herigate Sites
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico is the Latin American country with the
most sites declared mankind heritage by the United Nations
Education, Science, and Culture Organization (UNESCO).
</P>
<P>
Mexico, with 20 sites, is one of the countries with the
greatest numer of sites of this kind, said Jean Luxen, general
secretary of the U.N. Monuments and Sites International Council.

Argentina Will Attend the Venice Biennial Art Exhibition
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Artists from Argentina will take part in the
incoming Venice Biennial exhibition from June 15 to November 9,
announced the Culture Secretariat of this nation.
</P>
<P>
This year the Argentine artists will have a tent-pavillion with
a total surface of 200 square meters, in which they will exhibit
works of Gustavo Lopez Armentia, Ana Eckell, and Daniel Garcia,
whose paintings were awarded prizes in several national contests.

Piano and Violoncello German Artists To Play in Honduras
</P>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA -- The German artists Clemens Kroger (piano) and
Martin Vonhopffgarten (violoncello) will offer June 2 a concert of
classic music in the National Theater "Manuel Bonilla" of
Tegucigalpa.
</P>
<P>
The young German artists will perform in different sites to
encourage young people taste for the great masters classic music.

Works of Chilean Artists Exhibited in Paris
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- The exhibition "Chilean Visual Arts Today" is being
held May 29 to July 12 in Paris with 80 works, among paintings,
engravings, and installations belonging to the Chilean Museum of
Modern Art in Formation.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition is sponsored by the Chilean Foreign Relations
Ministry and the Ministry of Culture of France, to propagate the
good image about Chile.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people have visited the exhibition since its
inauguration and increased their knowledge about the Chilean
culture.
</P>
</TEXT>
