<DOCNO> XIE19970601.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sun Jun Upsets Hoyer-Larsen to Enter Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GLASGOW, Scotland, May 31 (Xinhua) -- China's Sun Jun beat
Olympic champion Poul-Erik Hoyer-Larsen here on Saturday to sail
into the world badminton championships men's singles final.
</P>
<P>
The former world junior champion sprinted to a 10-0 lead before
winning the first game 15-7.
</P>
<P>
Hoyer-Larsen, a left-hander who beat Sun at Swiss Open in three
sets this March, staged a comeback to win the second game 17-14.
</P>
<P>
A more lively Sun was never behind in the deciding game and
spurted to a 14-9 lead before Hoyer-Larsen returned a backhand
clear beyond the boundary line to concede loss.
</P>
<P>
"I expected to win today. I know I should win because I hold a
2-1 record against Hoyer-Larsen before this match," said Sun after
the 82-minute match.
</P>
<P>
Hoyer-Larsen said, "Sun had fantastic defence today... The
reason that I lost was Sun got the first set too easy. I made
mistakes I should not do."
</P>
<P>
Hoyer-Larsen, 31, said he still wanted to play the next world
championships to be staged in Copenhagen, the Netherlands, in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"My major target now in the future will be to compete in 1999,"
said two-time All England Open champion.
</P>
<P>
In Sunday's final, Sun will take on another Dane Peter
Rasmussen, who downed defending champion Heryanto Arbi of
Indonesia in the other semifinal.
</P>
<P>
Rasmussen, who never beat Arbi in the past four encounters
since 1995, rallied from one set down to gain a 9-15, 15-9 and
15-2 victory in 76 minutes.
</P>
<P>
"Actually I didn't expect to win. His attacks are very
good... I just played relaxed. If you are too tense, you cannot
play your normal game," said Rasmussen after the match.
</P>
<P>
"I just take it easy and enjoy playing badminton," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
